  "doc_id": "24288",
  "text": "Older AEDs that have proven useful for the treatment of partial seizures (e.g., phenytoin, phenobarbital, carbamazepine, valproate) have several limitations. Only approximately 20-30% of patients with complex partial seizures become seizure free while taking these drugs. [CITATION_1] Many of the older agents have similar mechanisms of action: blockade of use-dependent sodium channels. With the exception of valproate, all are potent enzyme inducers of various CYP450 isozymes as well as uridine diphosphate-glucuronyltransferase, and thus have a wide variety of drug interactions. The kinetics of these drugs are also somewhat problematic. Phenytoin, for example, follows nonlinear kinetics and is highly protein bound; carbamazepine undergoes time-dependent auto-induction; and valproate, also a highly protein-bound agent, can be an enzyme inhibitor.",
